<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Kalmia microphylla </i>is a much branched, often matted shrub < 50 cm. The leaves are dark green and glossy. Flowers are deep pinkish-rose and saucer-shaped. Plants spread by underground rhizomes. The species occurs in mountains of the Cascades and northern Rocky Mountains. <i>K. polifolia </i>or <i>K. p. </i>var. <i>microphylla </i>are commonly used synonyms for this plant in California botanical literature. <br/>
<br/>
NatureServe (2007a) identifies a <i>Kalmia microphylla </i>saturated dwarf-shrubland alliance in the Pacific Northwest. Most stands of <i>K. microphylla </i>are small in California and often mixed with other indicator species of various woody or herbaceous wetland alliances. <i>K. microphylla </i>is associated with shrubdominated fens, growing among the shrubs <i>Rhododendron columbianum, Spiraea douglasii, Vaccinium uliginosum, </i>and mosses such as <i>Sphagnum teres </i>and <i>S. subsecundum </i>(Cooper and Wolf 2006, Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> The range of <i>Kalmia microphylla</i> includes montane to alpine elevations in the Klamath Mountains (M261A), Southern Cascades (M261Df ), and Warner Mountains (M261Gf ). Cooper and Wolf (2006) included nine surveys in a <i>Kalmia microphylla /Sphagnum subsecundum</i> association found in nutrient-poor, shrub-dominated fens of the Sierra Nevada (M261E). Other associations described by Taylor (1984, see Cheng 2004) include the <i>Calamagrostis muiriana- Kalmia microphylla</i> and the <i>Carex nigricans-Kalmia microphylla</i> associations for the Harvey Monroe Hall RNA in the Sierra Nevada. However, we assigned these to the <i>Calamagrostis muiriana</i> and <i>Carex nigricans</i> alliances, respectively. Potter (2005) also described a <i>Vaccinium cespitosum-Kalmia polifolia</i> association of moist high elevation meadows composed of a mixture of subshrubs and graminoids. We treat this association as a part of the <i>Vaccinium cespitosum</i> alliance. Other stands with <i>K. microphylla</i> have an overstory of <i>Pinus contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana</i> in montane fens. Potter (2005) included these stands in a <i>Pinus contorta/Vaccinium uliginosum-Rhododendron columbianum </i>association in the Sierra Nevada, which is comparable to the type that S. Smith (1998b) identified as <i>Kalmia microphylla /Carex aquatilis</i> association in higher-elevation, high-acidity cold sites with <i>Pinus contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana</i> and <i>Rhododendron columbianum</i> in the Warner Mountains and Cascades. Cooper and Wolf (2006) additionally created a <i>Rhododendron columbianum-Kalmia microphylla-Pinus contorta</i> association in nutrient-poor fens of the Sierra Nevada. We need further in-depth analysis of all of these related types before making final disposition on these associations with <i>K. microphylla</i> and related alliances. </div>
</div>

	

    
